00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:14.280
and we're going to engage
in a fireside chat format

00:01:14.280 --> 00:01:17.250
with a discussion on what
playing fair means to them,

00:01:17.250 --> 00:01:20.042
their principles, their
priorities, their challenges.

00:01:20.042 --> 00:01:21.750
And then if we have
some time at the end,

00:01:21.750 --> 00:01:25.200
we'll save it for you
guys to ask us some Q&amp;A,

00:01:25.200 --> 00:01:28.500
but nothing too hard.

00:01:28.500 --> 00:01:30.930
So when we started down
the path of playing fair,

00:01:30.930 --> 00:01:33.280
we started with two main goals.

00:01:33.280 --> 00:01:35.790
The first was that we wanted
a balanced in-app purchase

00:01:35.790 --> 00:01:37.150
economy.

00:01:37.150 --> 00:01:38.940
So if you think about
when you have a game

00:01:38.940 --> 00:01:42.600
and you have a
currency in your game,

00:01:42.600 --> 00:01:44.280
users pay money
for that currency.

00:01:44.280 --> 00:01:46.260
And so you're assigning
a monetary value

00:01:46.260 --> 00:01:47.830
to that currency.

00:01:47.830 --> 00:01:50.580
And we want you to be
able to preserve this

00:01:50.580 --> 00:01:53.870
so you control that and you
have full control over that.

00:01:53.870 --> 00:01:56.167
So that was the first
objective that we have.

00:01:56.167 --> 00:01:57.750
The second thing is
that we want to do

00:01:57.750 --> 00:01:59.970
the right thing for all users.

00:01:59.970 --> 00:02:01.810
And this means that
for good users,

00:02:01.810 --> 00:02:05.460
we want to provide a fair
and rewarding experience

00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:06.760
on our platform.

00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:10.199
But we also, importantly,
want to deter the bad users.

00:02:10.199 --> 00:02:12.090
And so when we combine
those two objectives,

00:02:12.090 --> 00:02:14.940
we hope that we can
achieve wins for you,

00:02:14.940 --> 00:02:18.228
the developers, the users,
and us as Google Play.

00:02:22.440 --> 00:02:24.100
So let me talk
about our principles

00:02:24.100 --> 00:02:26.680
to help us achieve these goals.

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:29.550
The first is that we want to do
the right thing for all users

00:02:29.550 --> 00:02:30.930
all the time.

00:02:30.930 --> 00:02:34.830
And this sounds like a really
big, googly, lofty goal.

00:02:34.830 --> 00:02:36.330
But really, it
starts with assuming

00:02:36.330 --> 00:02:39.240
that all users and all
developers are inherently good.

00:02:39.240 --> 00:02:40.860
And we really believe that.

00:02:40.860 --> 00:02:42.540
And so when they're
inherently good,

00:02:42.540 --> 00:02:45.510
we can provide them access
to all of our services.

00:02:45.510 --> 00:02:48.600
And that's a really
important trait to us.

00:02:48.600 --> 00:02:51.510
But we know from experience,
and probably you do, too,

00:02:51.510 --> 00:02:53.550
that not all users are good.

00:02:53.550 --> 00:02:55.320
And there's a very
small minority of them

00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:56.480
that aren't good.

00:02:56.480 --> 00:02:58.590
And so we have to
evaluate everything

00:02:58.590 --> 00:03:01.350
on a case-by-case basis or
an interaction-by-interaction

00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:02.550
basis.

00:03:02.550 --> 00:03:05.400
And to highlight this, let
me bring up an example.

00:03:05.400 --> 00:03:10.020
So who here in the audience has
made an in-app purchase before?

00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:11.700
That's a good showing.

00:03:11.700 --> 00:03:13.575
I know I have myself.

00:03:13.575 --> 00:03:17.340
And so let's assume that you
give a developer some money,

00:03:17.340 --> 00:03:18.990
and in turn, you get
in-game currency.

00:03:18.990 --> 00:03:20.500
Let's call them coins.

00:03:20.500 --> 00:03:24.090
Now let's suppose you want
to refund for your purchase.

00:03:24.090 --> 00:03:27.370
Well, in today's in-app purchase
world, you get your money back.

00:03:27.370 --> 00:03:31.060
But you also keep your coins,
which is a little bit weird.

00:03:31.060 --> 00:03:33.060
When you think about that
in the physical world,

00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:35.910
that would be like
going to buy a vacuum

00:03:35.910 --> 00:03:38.640
and wanting to return the
vacuum and get a refund,

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:40.380
but actually keeping the vacuum.

00:03:40.380 --> 00:03:42.360
And that's a little bit weird.

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:47.280
And so when you think about a
good user who wants a refund,

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:49.470
we believe that they should
be willing to give up

00:03:49.470 --> 00:03:53.040
their in-game currency
to get their money back.

00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:54.840
Now we think about the bad user.

00:03:54.840 --> 00:03:57.220
And they might not want
to give up their currency,

00:03:57.220 --> 00:03:59.500
but it's still the
right thing to do.

00:03:59.500 --> 00:04:04.230
And so in all cases, both the
good user and the bad user,

00:04:04.230 --> 00:04:06.570
giving up the currency
is the right thing to do.

00:04:06.570 --> 00:04:09.060
And we believe that.

00:04:09.060 --> 00:04:12.900
So we took these two principles,
and we combined them together,

00:04:12.900 --> 00:04:14.340
and we built an API.

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:17.950
And the API will allow
you, the developer,

00:04:17.950 --> 00:04:20.940
to access all of your
refunds for your games

00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:23.880
so that you can take back
the currency from the users,

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:25.470
whether they're
good or they're bad,

00:04:25.470 --> 00:04:27.290
and make your game
more balanced.

00:04:27.290 --> 00:04:29.830
And that's the big product
announcement we have today.

00:04:29.830 --> 00:04:31.710
So I'm going to hand it
over to David for him

00:04:31.710 --> 00:04:34.132
to talk more about this.

00:04:34.132 --> 00:04:35.340
DAVID RIPHAGEN: Thanks, John.

